  "prompt": "Why do e-commerce companies offset last row results when paginating products?",
  "response": "E-commerce companies typically offset last row results when paginating products for several important reasons:\n\n1. Consistent Page Size\n- Ensures each page displays a consistent number of items\n- Helps maintain a uniform user experience across different result sets\n- Prevents partial or inconsistent page lengths\n\n2. Database Efficiency\n- Allows efficient querying of database records\n- Uses SQL OFFSET and LIMIT clauses for performance optimization\n- Reduces unnecessary data retrieval and processing overhead\n\nExample SQL Query:\n```sql\nSELECT * FROM products\nLIMIT 20 OFFSET 40  // Fetches next 20 products after first 40\n```\n\n3. Performance Optimization\n- Reduces memory consumption\n- Minimizes data transfer between database and application\n- Enables faster page loading and scrolling\n\n4. Scalable Architecture\n- Supports large product catalogs\n- Enables handling of millions of items efficiently\n- Provides flexible pagination mechanisms\n\n5. User Experience\n- Enables smooth navigation through product listings\n- Supports pagination controls (next/previous pages)\n- Allows predictable browsing experience\n\nPagination strategies help balance between data accessibility, performance, and user interaction in e-commerce platforms.",
